ity, and impact. The final section explores ethical considerations in relation to public engagement as well as discussing the way that research communication fits into wider discussions about the impact of research, before concluding with a discussion around disseminating the success (or otherwise) of novel approaches to public engagement to wider groups, including public engagement practitioners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication in higher education. 0aUniversities and collegesxPublic relations. 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh  aCommunication.  aCreative.  aDigital Media.  aDissemination.  aEngagement.  aEvaluation.  aImpact.  aParticipants.  aResearch.  aSocial Media.1 aWeitkamp, Emma, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWeitkamp, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilkinson, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615340140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526153401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526153401/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles